public interface Tuple extends Iterable<Object>
A finite ordered list (otherwise sequence) of fixed length elements. The user of this interface has precise control over where in the tuple each element is placed. The user can access elements by their integer index (position in the tuple), and search for elements in the tuple. Unlike collections, tuples typically are finite and has a fixed length. Tuples typically allow pairs of elements t0 and b0 such that t0.equals(b0). More formally: The general rule for the identity of two n-tuples is (a0, a1, ..., an) = (b0, b1, ..., bn) if and only if a0 = b0, a1 = b1, ..., an = bn
  • A tuple may contain multiple instances of the same element, so tuple (1, 2, 2, 3) != (1, 2, 3)
  • Tuple elements are ordered: (1, 2, 3) != (3, 2, 1)
  • A tuple has a finite number of elements, while a set or a multiset may have an infinite number of elements.
The Tuple interface places additional stipulations, beyond those specified in the Iterable interface, on the contracts of the iterator, get, getOrDefault, equals, and hashCode methods. Declarations for other inherited methods are also included here for convenience. The Tuple interface provides two methods for positional (indexed) access to tuple elements. Tuples (like arrays) are zero based. project moonshine created 22.12.2022 11:41
